# Trivy CVE allowlist for the GHCR publish workflow.
#
# Format: plain-text, one CVE id per non-comment line. Trivy reads this
# file via its `--ignorefile` flag (wired up as `trivyignores:` in
# `.github/workflows/docker-publish.yml`) and excludes listed CVEs from
# the scan output before deciding the exit code.
#
# IMPORTANT: this file deliberately has NO `.yaml`/`.yml` extension.
# Trivy 0.65+ infers the ignorefile format from the filename: `.yaml` or
# `.yml` triggers the YAML schema parser, anything else (including no
# extension) is parsed as plain text. Bare `CVE-XXXX-YYYYY` lines are
# only valid in the plain-text format. If you rename this file, drop
# the extension or use `.trivyignore`.
#
# Conventions for additions:
#   - Add a comment block above each CVE (or related group of CVEs)
#     explaining the decision: which package, why it isn't exploitable in
#     Turbo EA's usage path, and the date / reviewer.
#   - Re-evaluate quarterly. Remove entries when the upstream fixes ship.
#   - Prefer fixing over allowlisting where a base-image bump or apk update
#     resolves the finding.
#
# Each runtime Dockerfile stage now runs `apk upgrade --no-cache` before
# its app payload, so apk-package CVEs in the live runtime images are
# fixed automatically when a patched .apk is available in the pinned
# Alpine release. Anything still listed below is either build-stage-only
# or shipped as an upstream binary that we cannot rebuild from this repo.
#
# The publish workflow currently runs Trivy with `exit-code: 0`
# (non-blocking) — findings are uploaded as SARIF to the Security tab.
# Flip `exit-code` to `1` in `docker-publish.yml` once the apk-upgrade
# chain has drained the backlog and we're comfortable that this
# allowlist captures everything we mean to accept.

